Bilateral subclavian steal syndrome. Bilateral atherosclerotic subclavian artery occlusion is rare.To describe the surgical treatment of a patient with symptomatic bilateral subclavian artery occlusion.A midline sternotomy and bilateral aorto-subclavian bypass was performed in a male with upper limb, exercise-induced vertigo.Postoperatively symptomatic improvement paralleled an increase in brachial systolic arterial blood pressure readings.Bypass grafting is the more durable option for subclavian artery occlusion, as angioplasty with or without stenting is associated with a higher rate of late stenosis.